51
00:03:08.396 --> 00:03:10.481
are motivated by chemistry.

52
00:03:10.899 --> 00:03:13.776
However, keep in mind
that there are also those inspired

53
00:03:13.776 --> 00:03:17.030
by quantum machine learning
and other near-term

54
00:03:17.071 --> 00:03:20.617
algorithms like quantum
approximate optimization algorithms.

55
00:03:21.492 --> 00:03:24.787
Let's discuss
some common choices for a chemistry ansatz.

56
00:03:25.455 --> 00:03:27.916
Unitary coupled cluster or UCC

57
00:03:28.208 --> 00:03:32.003
is the method originally proposed
in the first VQE publication,

58
00:03:32.295 --> 00:03:35.340
and it's commonly used in quantum
chemistry problems.

59
00:03:36.007 --> 00:03:38.676
Typically,
when we parameterized a quantum state,

60
00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:41.930
we work with exponentially
many parameters.

61
00:03:42.347 --> 00:03:45.058
However, to make preparation
circuits efficient,

62
00:03:45.308 --> 00:03:47.644
we need the polynomial number
of operations

63
00:03:47.644 --> 00:03:51.314
and therefore a polynomial number
of parameters.

64
00:03:51.814 --> 00:03:55.985
UCC is an example of a way of preparing
a trial state with such a circuit

65
00:03:56.319 --> 00:03:59.239
and it derives from a coupled cluster
method,

66
00:03:59.239 --> 00:04:01.866
which is the golden standard in quantum
chemistry.

67
00:04:02.575 --> 00:04:05.703
The most common choice is the unitary
coupled cluster

68
00:04:05.703 --> 00:04:10.500
singles and doubles
ansatz or UCCSD in short.

69
00:04:11.125 --> 00:04:16.630
Because UCCSD is motivated by specific
electronic configuration of a problem,

70
00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:21.928
we need to ensure we have a reference
state which properly reflects the system.

71
00:04:22.553 --> 00:04:24.596
This is the Hartree-Fock state.

72
00:04:24.597 --> 00:04:29.435
UCCSD ansatz usually gives
a good approximation of the ground state

73
00:04:29.435 --> 00:04:35.233
because it captures single and double
electron excitations in a given molecule.

74
00:04:35.233 --> 00:04:38.528
The number of parameters in UCCSD scales

75
00:04:38.528 --> 00:04:42.365
quadratically with the number of spin
orbitals.

76
00:04:42.365 --> 00:04:46.035
UCCSD can be very well
tailored to a problem,

77
00:04:46.286 --> 00:04:50.456
but unfortunately, quadratic scaling
still leads to very deep circuits

78
00:04:50.623 --> 00:04:53.209
which are difficult for current quantum
computers.

79
00:04:54.002 --> 00:04:58.089
This is why IBM researchers proposed
more heuristic approach,

80
00:04:58.339 --> 00:05:02.510
where one can tailor a variational form
to the underlying hardware

81
00:05:02.927 --> 00:05:06.180
which results in an efficiently
executable circuit.

82
00:05:06.848 --> 00:05:10.601
That is, trial states are parameterized
by quantum gates

83
00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:15.106
and are adapted
to the available physical device.

84
00:05:15.106 --> 00:05:18.735
This is a very heuristic approach
that is hardware friendly.

85
00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:22.989
Based on these examples, let's take a look
at the spectrum of possibilities

86
00:05:22.989 --> 00:05:26.075
that we have to express
our variational form.

87
00:05:26.868 --> 00:05:29.829
A lot of these
are already implemented in Qiskit

88
00:05:30.038 --> 00:05:32.623
so I encourage you to try out for yourself

89
00:05:32.790 --> 00:05:35.710
which one is the most suitable
for the problem you're trying to solve.

90
00:05:36.502 --> 00:05:40.214
If we look at the graph, on the one hand
we have the very heuristic

91
00:05:40.214 --> 00:05:41.466
variational forms.

92
00:05:41.466 --> 00:05:44.635
When the problem specificity is low, but

93
00:05:44.635 --> 00:05:47.513
they are designed to be implemented
on the real hardware.

94
00:05:48.306 --> 00:05:51.059
They are also highly expressive,
all in the sense

95
00:05:51.059 --> 00:05:54.103
that one can express
many quantum states with them.

96
00:05:54.979 --> 00:05:57.815
However,
a problem that may occur in the later

97
00:05:57.815 --> 00:06:00.818
stage of classical optimization
is encountering

98
00:06:00.818 --> 00:06:04.989
the so-called barren plateau,
which we will discuss in the next module.

99
00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:09.368
On the other hand,
we have a highly problem specific unitary

100
00:06:09.369 --> 00:06:14.248
coupled cluster, which works
excellent in classical chemistry but

